Job Advocate is a revolutionary web based and mobile application thatenrolls professional job seekers as entrepreneurs and provides a resourcecenter to coordinate benefits, receive payments, track taxes, offer expertconsultations and seek projects. Job Advocate will be using intuitivetechnology to create better job matches and increase overall user experience. THE PROBLEMThe freelance marketplace industry is currently seeing enormous growth. In fact, demand is currently set to outpace supply. A recent study by Staffing Industry Analysts (SIA) stated thatmid-market and enterprise companies are turning to online freelancers at recordpace.The SIA team reports that 10% of all firms are now employing a contingent workforce. This is a dramatic increase from SIA’s study the previous year, where estimates were at 3%. In fact, it is projected that by 2020, freelancers are expected to make up 50% of the full time workforce! Contract workers help businesses reduce costs while receiving exceptional work. Currently the online freelance platforms focus primarily on IT, software development and multimedia professionals overseas. There is a true need for a US-based platform that offers professional services such as finance, management, accounting and legal work.THE SOLUTIONJob Advocate is a revolutionary web based and mobile application that enrolls professional job seekers as entrepreneurs and provides a resource center to coordinate benefits, receive payments, track taxes, offer expert advice, and seek projects. Job Advocate will be using intuitive technology to create better job matches and increase overall user experience.   JOB ADVOCATE BENEFITS Saves time and money for employers who do not wish to     add to payroll; 
Seamlessly connects employers and freelancers through     innovative matching technology;
Offers a resource center full of tools to assist     freelancers in creating, maintaining and growing their independent     businesses;
Documents, protects and stores all payments made     through the Job Advocate platform.

THE FREELANCE ONLINE EMPLOYMENT SERVICES COMPETITIONThe online freelance employment industry has developed rapidly in the past decade. General freelance marketplaces are now the largest platforms. As the industry’s first movers, these marketplaces established brand recognition, grew their user base and made many acquisitions. Job Advocate will compete in this segment but will offer added features and focus on job categories that its competitors do not.COMPETITIVE ADVANTAGEAdvantage #1Innovative prediction and matching technology that will use algorithms and metatags to create convenience and save time and money for both parties.Advantage #2Job Advocate will focus on unmet needs in employer demand. This will mean recruiting freelancers with a focus in such professional skills as finance,  accounting, management and marketing. These are underserved markets on competitor sites.Advantage #3Resource center that attracts and aids freelancers in starting and operating their businesses. HOW IT WORKSJob Advocate will enlist both employer and freelancers on its marketplace platform. Job Advocate will be a full-service marketplace and its technology will offer added benefits such as talent screening and matching, which will be an added convenience for employers and freelancers. This will also help Job Advocate to combat information asymmetry, which is prevalent in existing services.The Job Advocate platform will be the “middle man” for each job posting and consequent hiring. Communication, work and invoicing will all be stored through the company’s cloud-based storage system. In addition to finding contract work, freelancers will have access to a resource center, which will host legal resources, tax advisory, benefit services, payment services, a personal coach resource, and more. It is Job Advocate’s goal to partner freelancers so that they may become independent, productive, educated, and aware of their job market value.   TARGET INDUSTRIESJob Advocate will open its marketplace to many types of freelancers, but with a focus on skilled and licensed professionals. While its largest competitors (Elance, Freelancer and oDesk) are known to primarily emphasize IT, software development and design and multi-media, Job Advocate will focus on the future of freelance business—white collar workers.  37% of job postings on Elance come from the industry segment of IT and Programming, while only 2% comes from finance and management. This is in disparity to the demand in the market. The Global Skills in Demand chart shows that 88% of companies are looking for skilled workers in the area of finance and management, followed by sales and marketing. Job Advocate will focus on enrolling users who meet the criteria demanded by the market. In today’s world, more and more traditional workers are turning to freelancing due to the limited available jobs, the independence and quality of life brought on by freelancing, and the ability to control how much money is charged per job. Job Advocate believes that it can locate and convert these ready and available skilled workers and create an in-demand freelance marketplace.WHO ARE FREELANCERS?The number of freelance workers in the US is rapidly growing. A 2010 Intuit survey projects that more than 40 percent of the U.S. workforce would be contingent workers by 2020. More recently, a lobbying group called It’s My Business estimated there are 10.3 million independent contractors working in the U.S. today. Freelancers Union, meanwhile, says 42 million workers, or one-third of the current US labor-force are already freelancers.These freelancers come from many different backgrounds and are looking for flexibility and freedom in their work. Following the recent economic downturn, the employment rate has recovered at a frustratingly slow pace, except in one area: temporary, contingent, and independent workers. Between 2009 and 2012, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the number of temporary employees rose by 29%. During the labor market crash of 2008, many previous full-time employees became freelancers out of necessity before realizing the benefits that come along with being independent. A glimpse into the mind of this target market can be seen to the right. COMPANIES HIRING FREELANCERSCompanies of all sizes and industries are now hiring freelance workers. As can be seen on the previous page, companies are now looking to contract out more professional and licensed services such as finance and management. These skills apply to all types of businesses.While in the past freelancers have focused on marketing their services to penny-pinching start ups and SMBs, today more and more large corporations with higher budgets are entering into the marketplace. They are looking for experienced professionals for contract work in order to limit payroll while completing projects in a timely manner. 42% of employers said they anticipate hiring more freelancers in 2014 than the previous year.It is projected that by 2020, freelancers could make up 50%of the full time work force.Employers are demanding more white collar, professional freelancers. ONGOING MARKETING STRATEGYOnce Job Advocate is fully operation and competing within the market, it will implement a continued marketing strategy. This strategy will  involve traditional media, events and networking, online advertising and social media marketing. USER ACQUISITIONJob Advocate will use its sales and marketing plan to acquire new users. In year 1, the website will enroll over 40,000 freelancers and over 16,000 employers. This will increase to a total of  2.5 million freelancers in year 5 and over 400,000 employers.The average employer will post 5 jobs per year by year 5, and an average of 40% of posted jobs will be awarded. These numbers are more conservative than industry standard for the sake of proper risk planning in the business plan.FINANCIAL SUMMARYJob Advocate is targeting significant growth over the next several years, and is seeking an investment of $500,000 to support this growth. The company is searching for investment partners in order to bring the platform to market and support the company's growth plan, vision and management style. The majority of funds raised will go directly to driving the completion and launch of version 1.0, and early customer acquisition and  development.
